{{Infobox institute | name = Istituto per le Applicazioni del Calcolo "Mauro Picone" | image = | image_upright = | alt = | caption = | latin_name = | motto = | founder = [[Mauro Picone]] | established = 1927 | mission = | focus = | president = | ceo = | chairman = | head_label = | head = | faculty = | adjunct_faculty = | staff = | key_people = | budget = | endowment = | debt = | num_members = | subsidiaries = | owner = | former_name = {{plainlist| *Istituto di Calcolo per l'Analisi Numerica (1927–1932)<ref>See {{harv|Ghizzetti|1986|p=111}}.</ref> *Istituto Nazionale per le Applicazioni del Calcolo (INAC) (1932–1975)<ref name="G.and.F">See {{harv|Fichera|1995|pp=10–11}}, {{harv|Fichera|1999|p=297}}, {{harv|Ghizzetti|1986|p=111}}.</ref>}} | location = | city = | state = Italy | province = | country = | coor = | address = {{plainlist| *Via dei Taurini 19, *00185 Roma}} | website = http://www.iac.rm.cnr.it | dissolved = | footnotes = }} The '''Istituto per le Applicazioni del Calcolo Mauro Picone''' ({{lang-en|Institute for Calculus Applications "Mauro Picone"}}), abbreviated '''IAC''', is an [[applied mathematics]] [[institute]], part of the [[Consiglio Nazionale delle Ricerche]]. It was founded in 1927 as a private research institute by [[Mauro Picone]],<ref name="G.and.F" /> and as such it is considered the first applied and computational mathematics institute of such kind ever founded.<ref>{{harv|Fichera|1995|pp=10–11}}, {{harv|Fichera|1999|p=297}}, {{harv|Benzi|2005|loc=p. 3 of the preprint version}} and the references cited in this latter one.</ref>
==Historical notes== The IAC was founded 1927 by Mauro Picone,<ref name="G.and.F" /> while working an the [[University of Naples Federico II]] and at the [[Istituto Universitario Navale]] as professor of [[infinitesimal calculus]].<ref>See {{harv|Ghizzetti|1986|p=111}}, {{harv|De Angelis|Sbordone|1999|p=7}}, {{harv|Fichera|1995|pp=10–11}}, {{harv|Fichera|1999|p=297}}, {{harvtxt|Ghizzetti|1986|p=111}} states explicitly his professorship, while {{harvtxt|De Angelis|Sbordone|1999|p=7}} describes briefly his involvement in teaching at the Istituto Universitario Navale.</ref> [[Luigi Amoroso]] also contributed to the founding of the institute, by providing to his former ''[[Scuola Normale Superiore|Normale]]'' schoolfellow Picone the funding for the creation of the Institute by means of the [[Banco di Napoli]].<ref>See {{Harvtxt|Fichera|1950|p=1}}, {{Harvtxt|Fichera|1986|p=81}}, {{Harvtxt|Fichera|1999|p=307}} and {{Harvtxt|Benzi|2005|loc=p. 3 of the preprint version}}.</ref> It was only in 1932, when Picone moved from the University of Naples to the [[Sapienza University of Rome]], that the Institute became part of the Italian National Research Council.<ref>See for example {{harv|Ghizzetti|1986|p=111}}, {{harv|De Angelis|Sbordone|1999|p=7}}, {{Harvtxt|Fichera|1986|p=81}}, {{Harv|Fichera|1999|p=307}}, {{Harv|Benzi|2005|loc=p. 3 of the preprint version}}, {{Harv|Benzi|Toscano|2005|p=114}}: however many other published biographical and/or research achievements surveys on Mauro Picone cite this fact.</ref>
